WEBVTT

1
00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:20.576
Hello.

2
00:02:20.600 --> 00:02:21.880
It's Packenham.

3
00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:24.816
Your name comes up.

4
00:02:24.840 --> 00:02:27.576
There's a PolAir plane
on the tarmac waiting for you.

5
00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:29.600
You're flying out to Nulla for a homicide.

6
00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:32.736
Why me?

7
00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:34.200
You need a tan.

8
00:02:36.400 --> 00:02:38.096
Who have I got?

9
00:02:38.120 --> 00:02:39.880
Local detective from the area.

10
00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:44.800
Don't give me the "I only
work alone" bullshit. Ivan.

11
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.280
It's a few days. You'll survive.

12
00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:32.920
Yeah. yeah. I'm coming.

13
00:03:34.200 --> 00:03:35.920
Watch the house.

14
00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:46.216
I'll be lucky to make the autopsy.

15
00:03:46.240 --> 00:03:49.536
Can you just focus on the road. please?

16
00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:52.216
Could you try to sound
a bit less like my mother?

17
00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:56.056
Sorry. Nell.
I'm sure it's just first-day nerves.

18
00:03:56.080 --> 00:03:59.360
It's more than that.
What do you need to hear from me?

19
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.096
Tell me this is not going
to be a shit show. Cal.

20
00:04:05.120 --> 00:04:07.600
This is not going to be a shit show. Nell.

21
00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:32.896
Good morning. Detective.

22
00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:34.920
Beginning our descent into Nulla.

23
00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:38.080
Might be a little rough coming in.

24
00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:03.440
Thanks.

25
00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:16.736
I thought we got rid of you.

26
00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:19.040
Yeah. It's good to see you. too. Ray.

27
00:05:56.600 --> 00:05:59.440
Are you here for the decapitation?

28
00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:02.720
What? Lucic.

29
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.016
Yes.

30
00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:07.456
Yuri Sedov. I'm the airport manager.

31
00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:08.736
That's a nice hat.

32
00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:10.696
I'm expecting a lift.

33
00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:11.840
Not here.

34
00:06:13.280 --> 00:06:14.696
Is there somewhere I can wait?

35
00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:18.256
The chairman's lounge
is closed for renovations.

36
00:06:18.280 --> 00:06:20.456
but you can wait right here
on the tarmac.

37
00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:24.696
or I can offer you some refreshments.

38
00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:25.896
Please.

39
00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:27.080
Yes.

40
00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:33.400
Sparkling water is $10. Beer. $20.

41
00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:36.440
Alright.

42
00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:40.080
Airport prices!

43
00:07:11.360 --> 00:07:13.216
Detective.

44
00:07:13.240 --> 00:07:15.656
Nell Buchanan. Ivan Lucic.

45
00:07:15.680 --> 00:07:17.696
I got here as fast as I could.

46
00:07:17.720 --> 00:07:20.256
Do you want to go
to the motel first. freshen up?

47
00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:22.256
I'll go straight to the mine.

48
00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:23.816
He's been down there long enough.

49
00:07:23.840 --> 00:07:25.040
OK.

50
00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:35.320
This is my first homicide.
so I appreciate it.

51
00:07:37.880 --> 00:07:39.040
Water?

52
00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:41.760
Good.

53
00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:51.656
Victim is Jonas McGee. 42. ex-con.

54
00:07:51.680 --> 00:07:55.256
He was found at the bottom
of his opal mine. decapitated.

55
00:07:55.280 --> 00:07:56.800
Head was in his lap.

56
00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:07.760
Do we know who called it in?

57
00:08:10.360 --> 00:08:14.320
Was an anonymous tip-off.
so it's probably a ratter.

58
00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:20.576
A what?

59
00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:24.256
It's an opal thief around here.

60
00:08:24.280 --> 00:08:27.816
They scurry down your mine at night

61
00:08:27.840 --> 00:08:31.496
and steal your opals
while you sleep. like a rat.

62
00:08:31.520 --> 00:08:33.376
Sort of.

63
00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:34.800
Weird name.

64
00:08:36.320 --> 00:08:39.216
I don't know why they'd call it in...

65
00:08:39.240 --> 00:08:41.600
risk implicating themselves for murder.

66
00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:44.200
Right thing to do. I guess.

67
00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:49.040
Listen. the local station
is actually not that far.

68
00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:52.736
Do you want to stop in.
meet the sergeant?

69
00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:54.080
No.

70
00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:01.720
It might be good to introduce yourself...

71
00:09:03.120 --> 00:09:04.880
just avoid a pissing contest.

72
00:10:07.160 --> 00:10:09.120
I'm sleeping. Yes. you are.

73
00:10:11.280 --> 00:10:13.536
I'm Detective Ivan Lucic.

74
00:10:13.560 --> 00:10:14.936
Homicide.

75
00:10:14.960 --> 00:10:17.976
I'm sorry. I'm... catching a bit of shut-eye.

76
00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:19.600
I've been up all night here. Detective.

77
00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:24.736
First time. is it. in Nulla?

78
00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:26.576
I haven't had the pleasure before.

79
00:10:26.600 --> 00:10:29.536
I think you'll find we're
a backward. violent. inbred bunch.

80
00:10:29.560 --> 00:10:31.280
but at least the parking's free.

81
00:10:33.920 --> 00:10:34.960
Sergeant Richter.

82
00:10:36.920 --> 00:10:40.176
Very good. This is Detective Buchanan.

83
00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:42.640
She will be assisting me
with my investigation.

84
00:10:44.240 --> 00:10:46.240
Detective. Good.

85
00:10:47.640 --> 00:10:51.776
I was stationed here
when I was in uniform. so...

86
00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:55.096
I taught young Narelle
everything she knows.

87
00:10:55.120 --> 00:10:57.160
Now she's back for more.

88
00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.616
Tell me what you know
about the anonymous caller.

89
00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:04.056
The ratter?

90
00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:07.016
How do we know they're a... ratter?

91
00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:08.256
Well. no-one else is going to be down

92
00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:10.056
someone else's hole after midnight.

93
00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:12.656
Do you have a name?

94
00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:14.776
Better than that -
we've got him in the lockup.

95
00:11:14.800 --> 00:11:16.256
Narelle knows where it is.

96
00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:17.280
Very good.

97
00:11:18.960 --> 00:11:20.576
Patricia.

98
00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:22.496
It's this way.

99
00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:23.600
Jesus.

100
00:11:42.480 --> 00:11:43.960
Kyle Torshack?

101
00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:49.096
Where's the uniform?

102
00:11:49.120 --> 00:11:50.760
Where's your manners?

103
00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.496
Why don't you tell me
what happened? Kyle?

104
00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:04.016
Have you seen my face?

105
00:12:04.040 --> 00:12:05.976
I'm looking at it.

106
00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:07.400
It doesn't look good.

107
00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:14.280
Is that a question. Detective?

108
00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:18.320
Tell me what a ratter is. Kyle.

109
00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:22.256
It's a dog act.

110
00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:23.880
Are you one?

111
00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:26.000
Nah.

112
00:12:30.640 --> 00:12:33.696
Jonas McGee is dead.

113
00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:35.896
His head's been chopped off.

114
00:12:35.920 --> 00:12:38.680
He's down his mineshaft
out on the West Ridge.

115
00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:42.280
His head is just lying there. off.

116
00:12:45.520 --> 00:12:46.800
Is that you?

117
00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:50.440
No.

118
00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:52.920
Who did this to your face?

119
00:12:54.040 --> 00:12:55.576
Mick The Brick Shithouse.

120
00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:58.856
Passed him on the way in. The whistler?

121
00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:00.736
Yeah. Suits him. doesn't it?

122
00:13:00.760 --> 00:13:03.216
Keeping me bottom of the food chain.

123
00:13:03.240 --> 00:13:05.616
But so are mosquitoes.
and they're the deadliest...

124
00:13:05.640 --> 00:13:07.176
thing on the planet.

125
00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:09.840
Pathogens.

126
00:13:12.560 --> 00:13:16.136
Can anyone verify
where you were last night. Kyle?

127
00:13:16.160 --> 00:13:17.216
Yeah.

128
00:13:17.240 --> 00:13:19.456
I finished my shift at the hospital.

129
00:13:19.480 --> 00:13:22.576
and I was driving home
when her boss pulled me over.

130
00:13:22.600 --> 00:13:24.040
She's not my boss. Kyle.

131
00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:26.776
What'd she say?

132
00:13:26.800 --> 00:13:29.496
Routine questions.

133
00:13:29.520 --> 00:13:30.880
And here we are.

134
00:13:43.600 --> 00:13:45.120
Do you know Jonas McGee?

135
00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:48.840
Yeah.

136
00:13:54.560 --> 00:13:55.800
How do you know each other?

137
00:13:58.000 --> 00:13:59.736
What?

138
00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:03.680
Tell Detective Lucic
how you know Jonas McGee.

139
00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:08.080
He was my uncle.

140
00:14:41.120 --> 00:14:43.816
His hospital alibi checks out.

141
00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:45.416
He'll be alright.

142
00:14:45.440 --> 00:14:47.600
I made sure it didn't get out of hand.

143
00:14:50.080 --> 00:14:52.536
Leaving a cell door open

144
00:14:52.560 --> 00:14:55.096
while a person of interest
is violently assaulted

145
00:14:55.120 --> 00:14:58.040
is not how I run
a murder investigation. Sergeant.

146
00:14:59.560 --> 00:15:02.096
Well. I've been running
this station a long time. Detective.

147
00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:05.856
and we have a thing here
called self-policing.

148
00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:07.080
These people...

149
00:15:08.280 --> 00:15:10.976
they haven't got much.
except hope in the ground -

150
00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:12.736
and not much of that either.

151
00:15:12.760 --> 00:15:15.376
So. when they strike opal. believe me...

152
00:15:15.400 --> 00:15:17.656
only thing worse than being
a murderer around here

153
00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:18.680
is being a ratter.

154
00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:34.856
Lovely.

155
00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:36.936
Yeah.

156
00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:38.816
How long were you here?

157
00:15:38.840 --> 00:15:40.656
Three years.

158
00:15:40.680 --> 00:15:42.760
I was under Richter for three years.

159
00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:46.456
So. you knew the murder victim?

160
00:15:46.480 --> 00:15:49.616
No. he was in prison. but I knew of him.

161
00:15:49.640 --> 00:15:52.496
That's why they assigned you -
local knowledge.

162
00:15:52.520 --> 00:15:54.256
Yeah. that would make sense.

163
00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:56.480
Why did you leave? Why did...?

164
00:16:00.320 --> 00:16:02.536
I was transferred.

165
00:16:02.560 --> 00:16:03.760
What for?

166
00:16:06.240 --> 00:16:09.616
I didn't understand my job description.

167
00:16:09.640 --> 00:16:11.160
What did you think it was?

168
00:16:14.320 --> 00:16:17.560
Charging people for committing crimes.

169
00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:30.536
Most of the mines dried up years ago.

170
00:16:30.560 --> 00:16:33.696
but people keep digging.
hoping it'll pay off.

171
00:16:33.720 --> 00:16:35.360
Jonas McGee was one of them.

172
00:16:36.520 --> 00:16:38.440
His claim's out this way.

173
00:17:10.040 --> 00:17:11.416
Carole.

174
00:17:11.440 --> 00:17:12.616
Ivan.

175
00:17:12.640 --> 00:17:14.280
Nell. Carole.

176
00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:18.576
Dr Carole Ness. forensic pathologist.

177
00:17:18.600 --> 00:17:20.656
Nice to meet you. You flying solo?

178
00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:23.496
Yeah. just me and the flies.

179
00:17:23.520 --> 00:17:24.736
Tell me things. Carole.

180
00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:27.336
There's no fresh tyre marks.

181
00:17:27.360 --> 00:17:29.440
Footprints everywhere. Size 13.

182
00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:33.856
I'm a size 13.

183
00:17:33.880 --> 00:17:36.536
I knew you'd come crawling back.
Buchanan.

184
00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:38.696
Well. I'm only human. Garry.

185
00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:41.480
G'day. Garry Ahern.
I've been holding your head for you.

186
00:17:43.440 --> 00:17:44.856
You verified the tip-off?

187
00:17:44.880 --> 00:17:46.016
Yeah.

188
00:17:46.040 --> 00:17:48.416
Yeah. I don't want to jump the gun
on your investigation.

189
00:17:48.440 --> 00:17:51.680
but judging by the look on his face.
he got a bit of a surprise.

190
00:17:57.040 --> 00:17:58.880
Hole's this way.

191
00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:17.016
You been down yet?

192
00:18:17.040 --> 00:18:18.480
Nah. That's your job.

193
00:19:12.480 --> 00:19:13.600
Empty lap.

194
00:19:22.480 --> 00:19:23.720
No head.

195
00:19:38.440 --> 00:19:39.680
This way.

196
00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:06.000
Police. Stop!

197
00:20:12.120 --> 00:20:13.280
Dead end.

198
00:20:34.160 --> 00:20:35.456
You heard that?

199
00:20:35.480 --> 00:20:37.720
Yeah. Yeah. I heard that.

200
00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.176
Sorry.

201
00:20:42.200 --> 00:20:43.520
Good.

202
00:20:54.280 --> 00:20:55.976
One. two. three.

203
00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:58.456
I am enough.

204
00:20:58.480 --> 00:21:01.056
I am... enough.

205
00:21:01.080 --> 00:21:04.856
As you breathe in now.
on your next inhale...

206
00:21:04.880 --> 00:21:08.736
I am... enough.
..I want you to picture a sunset.

207
00:21:08.760 --> 00:21:11.680
feeling that sunshine on your face.

208
00:21:14.920 --> 00:21:16.936
Garry. Yeah?

209
00:21:16.960 --> 00:21:19.440
Do you mind if I call you Garry?
Everyone calls me Garry. mate.

210
00:21:21.200 --> 00:21:23.016
Where's the head. Garry?

211
00:21:23.040 --> 00:21:25.256
Are you taking the piss?

212
00:21:25.280 --> 00:21:27.056
You had one job.

213
00:21:27.080 --> 00:21:28.576
Someone's been down there. Garry.

214
00:21:28.600 --> 00:21:29.656
It's not my fault. mate.

215
00:21:29.680 --> 00:21:31.616
There are literally
miles of tunnels down there.

216
00:21:31.640 --> 00:21:33.280
It's like a bloody rabbit warren. yeah?

217
00:21:35.560 --> 00:21:36.720
Find the head. Garry.

218
00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:02.960
Who lives over there?

219
00:22:05.360 --> 00:22:06.440
Kyle's mum.

220
00:22:07.520 --> 00:22:09.040
Don't expect a cup of tea.

221
00:22:11.400 --> 00:22:12.760
I'm sorry for your loss. Ada.

222
00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.056
I'm sure it was a long night.

223
00:22:16.080 --> 00:22:18.136
Yeah. I slept most of it.

224
00:22:18.160 --> 00:22:20.640
Had to take a couple of pills
to knock myself out.

225
00:22:23.120 --> 00:22:25.296
What time was that. Ada?

226
00:22:25.320 --> 00:22:27.400
Do you mind if I call you Ada?

227
00:22:28.480 --> 00:22:31.680
So. you didn't... see anything?

228
00:22:33.240 --> 00:22:34.456
You didn't hear anything?

229
00:22:34.480 --> 00:22:37.176
I didn't even know that
Jonas had hit pay dirt.

230
00:22:37.200 --> 00:22:38.320
Really?

231
00:22:40.240 --> 00:22:41.656
He's your brother?

232
00:22:41.680 --> 00:22:42.960
Yeah. Were you close?

233
00:22:43.960 --> 00:22:46.080
We were neighbours but we didn't talk.

234
00:22:50.200 --> 00:22:52.576
You live here with your son. Kyle?

235
00:22:52.600 --> 00:22:54.336
Yeah. I do. You got a problem with that?

236
00:22:54.360 --> 00:22:55.360
No.

237
00:22:57.080 --> 00:22:58.736
No. I...

238
00:22:58.760 --> 00:23:00.120
I think you're very lucky.

239
00:23:02.200 --> 00:23:04.256
Why weren't you and Jonas close?

240
00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:05.656
Well. we were.

241
00:23:05.680 --> 00:23:07.816
Then he got in with
a bunch of religious nutters

242
00:23:07.840 --> 00:23:09.816
with David and that mob.

243
00:23:09.840 --> 00:23:11.856
Who's David?

244
00:23:11.880 --> 00:23:13.896
He...

245
00:23:13.920 --> 00:23:17.136
runs a commune up here.

246
00:23:17.160 --> 00:23:19.056
The Third Row.

247
00:23:19.080 --> 00:23:21.936
I moved up here to get Jonas out of it.

248
00:23:21.960 --> 00:23:23.800
He was too far gone. though?

249
00:23:24.920 --> 00:23:27.256
Then what? I...

250
00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:29.896
I stayed. I bought a claim for myself.

251
00:23:29.920 --> 00:23:32.456
Bought a claim.
the neighbouring one. for him

252
00:23:32.480 --> 00:23:35.016
so he could mine it
when he got out of prison.

253
00:23:35.040 --> 00:23:36.416
And?

254
00:23:36.440 --> 00:23:39.376
Never even talked to me.
Said I was a heathen.

255
00:23:39.400 --> 00:23:41.536
Was he close to anyone?

256
00:23:41.560 --> 00:23:43.816
There was one guy that Jonas
took under his wing

257
00:23:43.840 --> 00:23:45.456
when he was in prison.

258
00:23:45.480 --> 00:23:48.656
Yeah. he... he worked the mine a bit
when he got out. as well.

259
00:23:48.680 --> 00:23:50.256
What was his name?

260
00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:52.776
He didn't have a name.
We just called him The Giant.

261
00:23:52.800 --> 00:23:54.736
He's a man mountain.

262
00:23:54.760 --> 00:23:55.976
Man mountain?

263
00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:57.040
Man mountain.

264
00:24:00.400 --> 00:24:02.656
Did Jonas have other family?

265
00:24:02.680 --> 00:24:05.696
Yeah. My niece. his daughter. Elsie.

266
00:24:05.720 --> 00:24:07.160
Were they close?

267
00:24:08.840 --> 00:24:09.976
Let me put it like this.

268
00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:13.040
She had a restraining order on him.

269
00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:19.416
Where is his daughter?

270
00:24:19.440 --> 00:24:21.376
She left town years ago.

271
00:24:21.400 --> 00:24:22.936
Never met her.

272
00:24:22.960 --> 00:24:25.176
Talk to me. Carole.

273
00:24:25.200 --> 00:24:27.296
I spoke to the coroner about the autopsy.

274
00:24:27.320 --> 00:24:30.296
Once I winch his body up.
I'll set up at the local hospital.

275
00:24:30.320 --> 00:24:32.176
run his prints. do a tox screen.

276
00:24:32.200 --> 00:24:33.696
I found a wallet.

277
00:24:33.720 --> 00:24:35.896
No phone. I can look for a phone.

278
00:24:35.920 --> 00:24:37.536
I'll check the database for his number.

279
00:24:37.560 --> 00:24:39.040
Where are you staying?

280
00:24:41.080 --> 00:24:42.600
There's only one place in town.

281
00:24:44.960 --> 00:24:48.456
You know. the killer might have
come back for the head.

282
00:24:48.480 --> 00:24:49.720
Collecting a trophy?

283
00:24:51.520 --> 00:24:52.760
Maybe.

284
00:24:54.600 --> 00:24:56.416
There's one thing I know.

285
00:24:56.440 --> 00:24:57.480
What's that?

286
00:24:59.120 --> 00:25:00.520
I brought the wrong clothes.

287
00:25:12.640 --> 00:25:14.160
Found his phone.

288
00:25:24.880 --> 00:25:26.296
There's no passcode on it.

289
00:25:26.320 --> 00:25:27.480
Outgoing calls?

290
00:25:30.840 --> 00:25:32.776
One contact.

291
00:25:32.800 --> 00:25:33.960
Elsie.

292
00:25:35.440 --> 00:25:36.640
That's his daughter.

293
00:25:38.040 --> 00:25:39.736
Yeah.

294
00:25:39.760 --> 00:25:41.200
What was he in for?

295
00:25:42.440 --> 00:25:45.000
Manslaughter. How long?

296
00:25:46.080 --> 00:25:47.800
Eight years. Out for two.

297
00:25:50.480 --> 00:25:52.360
How far back do the calls go?

298
00:25:53.560 --> 00:25:56.480
Just keeps going.

299
00:26:24.600 --> 00:26:25.800
What's in the box?

300
00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:44.320
Are you OK? Yeah.

301
00:27:01.040 --> 00:27:02.576
Carole?

302
00:27:02.600 --> 00:27:04.296
Yeah?

303
00:27:04.320 --> 00:27:05.536
You alright?

304
00:27:05.560 --> 00:27:07.240
Yeah. Why?

305
00:27:15.120 --> 00:27:16.576
Man Mountain.

306
00:27:16.600 --> 00:27:18.776
Hard to miss.

307
00:27:18.800 --> 00:27:19.960
We need a name.

308
00:27:21.160 --> 00:27:22.480
What's in the box?

309
00:27:31.760 --> 00:27:33.560
Jonas had serious opal.

310
00:27:40.600 --> 00:27:43.000
Nobody has $20.000 here.

311
00:27:45.160 --> 00:27:46.960
Nobody gets that lucky any more.

312
00:27:48.360 --> 00:27:49.936
Who buys and sells?

313
00:27:49.960 --> 00:27:51.000
The opals?

314
00:27:52.560 --> 00:27:53.896
Yes.

315
00:27:53.920 --> 00:27:55.416
The Irishman.

316
00:27:55.440 --> 00:27:56.760
He's down this way.

317
00:28:04.160 --> 00:28:05.680
That's who Ada was talking about.

318
00:28:07.040 --> 00:28:08.976
What do they call themselves again?

319
00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:10.320
The Third Row.

320
00:28:12.960 --> 00:28:18.056
Their commune up on the ridge.
that's the largest claim in town.

321
00:28:18.080 --> 00:28:20.216
Are there regulations on claim size?

322
00:28:20.240 --> 00:28:25.216
Yeah. but what they do is
they all just peg adjoining claims

323
00:28:25.240 --> 00:28:28.600
and pool all their resources to the seer.

324
00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:33.216
The seer?

325
00:28:33.240 --> 00:28:34.440
David Mamon.

326
00:28:35.760 --> 00:28:37.080
They say he's a prophet.

327
00:28:39.040 --> 00:28:40.680
Sounds like he's making one.

328
00:28:56.440 --> 00:28:58.816
Used to have two hands.
but they never went anywhere.

329
00:28:58.840 --> 00:29:00.480
Now it's just flipping me off.

330
00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:05.760
Irishman's this way.

331
00:29:16.880 --> 00:29:18.240
Everyone brings their opals here.

332
00:29:19.600 --> 00:29:21.320
Ratters? Yeah.

333
00:29:32.160 --> 00:29:33.200
Hello?

334
00:29:36.320 --> 00:29:37.656
Good... morning.

335
00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:39.256
Detectives Buchanan and Lucic.

336
00:29:39.280 --> 00:29:40.360
We're working a homicide.

337
00:29:41.720 --> 00:29:45.480
So. how can I help you. detectives?

338
00:29:47.760 --> 00:29:48.976
You're the Irishman?

339
00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:50.480
That's right. You're Scottish.

340
00:29:52.080 --> 00:29:54.400
That's very perceptive of you. Detective.

341
00:29:56.880 --> 00:29:58.040
Jonas McGee.

342
00:29:59.560 --> 00:30:03.496
He was found by a ratter
in his mine with his head cut off.

343
00:30:03.520 --> 00:30:05.600
Aye. Rest his soul.

344
00:30:12.640 --> 00:30:14.176
He sold opals through you.

345
00:30:14.200 --> 00:30:15.936
When he had them.

346
00:30:15.960 --> 00:30:18.656
I heard he was having a lucky run.

347
00:30:18.680 --> 00:30:21.296
Well. people like to talk.

348
00:30:21.320 --> 00:30:23.336
and when they don't know.
they make it up.

349
00:30:23.360 --> 00:30:25.056
Is that right? You know what I think?

350
00:30:25.080 --> 00:30:28.016
I think this ratter
went down there for a reason.

351
00:30:28.040 --> 00:30:31.000
I think they believed what they'd heard.

352
00:30:32.760 --> 00:30:34.640
So...

353
00:30:40.360 --> 00:30:42.880
Jonas sold me these.

354
00:30:48.360 --> 00:30:50.416
See. there's no dead spots.

355
00:30:50.440 --> 00:30:53.656
And that darker patch.
it brings out the colours.

356
00:30:53.680 --> 00:30:56.856
And that pattern there. that's star burst.

357
00:30:56.880 --> 00:30:58.760
That's what makes it so valuable.

358
00:30:59.800 --> 00:31:00.960
How valuable?

359
00:31:03.280 --> 00:31:04.560
20 grand. thereabouts.

360
00:31:11.320 --> 00:31:12.776
Who else knows?

361
00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:15.640
Well. I keep my mouth shut.
It's safer that way.

362
00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:22.120
There's a giant... man.

363
00:31:23.240 --> 00:31:24.816
Aye. You met Stan.

364
00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:27.016
Stan? Yeah. Stan the Man Mountain.

365
00:31:27.040 --> 00:31:28.176
I mean. that's what they call him.

366
00:31:28.200 --> 00:31:29.736
I don't think that's
his real surname. though.

367
00:31:29.760 --> 00:31:31.296
I'm looking for him.

368
00:31:31.320 --> 00:31:32.856
Well. you'll have to speak to the mayor.

369
00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:35.176
'cause he's the one who handles Stan.

370
00:31:35.200 --> 00:31:37.136
Really?

371
00:31:37.160 --> 00:31:38.576
Got it.

372
00:31:38.600 --> 00:31:40.216
Good.

373
00:31:40.240 --> 00:31:42.320
We'll be in touch.
Great. I look forward to it.

374
00:32:32.120 --> 00:32:34.176
That's him?

375
00:32:34.200 --> 00:32:37.936
Doug Tallon.
Yeah. You'll see this everywhere.

376
00:32:37.960 --> 00:32:40.960
He's the kit guy.
All the mining equipment.

377
00:32:42.080 --> 00:32:43.360
It's all him.

378
00:32:51.960 --> 00:32:53.840
Doug Tallon?

379
00:32:57.480 --> 00:32:59.536
Who's asking?

380
00:32:59.560 --> 00:33:02.496
Detective Lucic. Homicide.

381
00:33:02.520 --> 00:33:05.440
I'll give you 24 hours. Detective.

382
00:33:06.840 --> 00:33:08.496
Tell me more.

383
00:33:08.520 --> 00:33:10.880
Bit hot in the kitchen for you.
by the looks of things.

384
00:33:14.200 --> 00:33:17.016
Yeah. Welcome back. Narelle.
You miss us?

385
00:33:17.040 --> 00:33:19.416
It's 'Detective'. if titles are important.

386
00:33:19.440 --> 00:33:21.960
Ooh! Well. bully for you.

387
00:33:23.720 --> 00:33:27.456
I'm looking for the Man Mountain.
Mr Tallon.

388
00:33:27.480 --> 00:33:29.240
Do you mind if I call you Mr Tallon?

389
00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:32.896
Around here...

390
00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:35.696
most people call me Mr Mayor.

391
00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:37.696
You go around calling me Mr Tallon.

392
00:33:37.720 --> 00:33:40.016
well. I think I'm in trouble or something.

393
00:33:40.040 --> 00:33:41.976
There's no reason
you would be in trouble. is there?

394
00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:43.216
Not...

395
00:33:43.240 --> 00:33:45.360
that I can think of. Narelle.

396
00:33:46.480 --> 00:33:49.736
We're just solving the problems
of the world in here. Detective.

397
00:33:49.760 --> 00:33:51.336
Yep.

398
00:33:51.360 --> 00:33:55.136
Albeit with some relaxing bubbles
kicking in every now and again.

399
00:33:55.160 --> 00:33:57.856
courtesy of my associates.
Frank and Frankie.

400
00:33:57.880 --> 00:33:59.776
Cheers. Yeah. I remember.

401
00:33:59.800 --> 00:34:00.976
I bet you do.

402
00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:03.056
Little top-up. boys?

403
00:34:03.080 --> 00:34:04.936
Love it. Lydia.

404
00:34:04.960 --> 00:34:06.760
My darling. you complete me.

405
00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.096
My lady mayoress.

406
00:34:11.120 --> 00:34:15.216
Now. they are running
the Anne Boleyn case.

407
00:34:15.240 --> 00:34:17.136
So...

408
00:34:17.160 --> 00:34:18.456
the Man Mountain.

409
00:34:18.480 --> 00:34:21.536
Stanley. Stanley.

410
00:34:21.560 --> 00:34:25.176
No idea where he is.
Mind you. he's hard to miss.

411
00:34:25.200 --> 00:34:26.616
You got a phone number on him?

412
00:34:26.640 --> 00:34:27.896
There's no point.

413
00:34:27.920 --> 00:34:30.456
He doesn't talk.
You got an address on him?

414
00:34:30.480 --> 00:34:33.320
I'd love to see you get a dress
on him. Narelle. I tell you.

415
00:34:35.680 --> 00:34:38.720
Ignore him. Too many pina coladas.

416
00:34:40.040 --> 00:34:41.400
You got a card. detective?

417
00:34:42.960 --> 00:34:44.256
No.

418
00:34:44.280 --> 00:34:46.256
Well...

419
00:34:46.280 --> 00:34:47.896
we see Stanley.

420
00:34:47.920 --> 00:34:50.856
send you a smoke signal. won't we. boo?

421
00:34:50.880 --> 00:34:54.576
Yeah. We're here to help. detectives.

422
00:34:54.600 --> 00:34:56.840
Next time. bring your bathers?

423
00:35:25.560 --> 00:35:27.696
His fingerprints are
a confirmed match to the record.

424
00:35:27.720 --> 00:35:29.456
So is the blood type
on the blade of the axe.

425
00:35:29.480 --> 00:35:32.856
Now. the body shows complete
cervical disarticulation at C2.

426
00:35:32.880 --> 00:35:34.256
which is the upper vertebrae.

427
00:35:34.280 --> 00:35:37.576
Bilateral compound fractures
of both the tibia and fibula.

428
00:35:37.600 --> 00:35:40.536
Additional fractures to the pelvis.
ribs. and spine

429
00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:42.616
indicate high-energy axial compression.

430
00:35:42.640 --> 00:35:44.256
He was pushed down the mine shaft.

431
00:35:44.280 --> 00:35:45.960
Yeah. And beheaded after.

432
00:35:46.960 --> 00:35:48.936
"Are you the one to come?"

433
00:35:48.960 --> 00:35:50.296
Number three there.

434
00:35:50.320 --> 00:35:53.496
That's the position of the head
before our souvenir hunter took it.

435
00:35:53.520 --> 00:35:55.376
Time of death? Three days ago.

436
00:35:55.400 --> 00:35:58.336
I could be more precise if
I had the body in the 21st century.

437
00:35:58.360 --> 00:36:01.096
Was he unconscious when it happened?

438
00:36:01.120 --> 00:36:03.816
I hope so. Took three goes
to finish him off. same as...

439
00:36:03.840 --> 00:36:05.280
Mary. Queen of Scots.

440
00:36:07.640 --> 00:36:08.960
Yeah.

441
00:36:10.080 --> 00:36:11.560
With this.

442
00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:16.736
Saxon miner's axe.

443
00:36:16.760 --> 00:36:18.040
Medieval antique.

444
00:36:19.520 --> 00:36:20.696
Prints on that?

445
00:36:20.720 --> 00:36:23.120
No. Wiped clean.

446
00:36:24.200 --> 00:36:25.640
Old school.

447
00:37:03.240 --> 00:37:04.280
How can I help you?

448
00:37:05.760 --> 00:37:07.616
We're here to check in.

449
00:37:07.640 --> 00:37:09.576
You're the fuzz.

450
00:37:09.600 --> 00:37:12.416
You're here for the whole. like.
decapitation-business thing?

451
00:37:12.440 --> 00:37:14.136
Yeah. that's probably been
one of the best things

452
00:37:14.160 --> 00:37:15.896
ever happened to the Golden View Motel.

453
00:37:15.920 --> 00:37:17.736
Three rooms snapped up like that.

454
00:37:17.760 --> 00:37:19.160
Yep. There's three of us.

455
00:37:20.520 --> 00:37:23.216
Darryl. Do you mind if I call you...?

456
00:37:23.240 --> 00:37:28.376
Everyone used to call me Darryl.
but everyone calls me Dazzler now.

457
00:37:28.400 --> 00:37:30.320
'cause I'm a people's type
of person. you know?

458
00:37:31.880 --> 00:37:33.280
Key. please.

459
00:37:45.600 --> 00:37:47.456
Yeah. That's right. Yeah. That's you.

460
00:37:47.480 --> 00:37:49.696
Now. I've got a few house rules.

461
00:37:49.720 --> 00:37:51.696
So. number one. have fun.

462
00:37:51.720 --> 00:37:53.680
Number two. flush.
Number three. make...

463
00:38:58.640 --> 00:39:01.120
Such a weird guy.

464
00:39:03.160 --> 00:39:05.576
Not sure what his deal is yet.

465
00:39:05.600 --> 00:39:08.696
Have you asked him what his deal is?

466
00:39:08.720 --> 00:39:12.016
It's not really
that kind of thing. you know?

467
00:39:12.040 --> 00:39:14.896
There's more important questions
to ask than that.

468
00:39:14.920 --> 00:39:16.696
Like what?

469
00:39:16.720 --> 00:39:18.336
Like. "Hey. Ivan".

470
00:39:18.360 --> 00:39:21.040
"where do you think
this guy's severed head is?"

471
00:39:23.720 --> 00:39:26.816
I cannot believe they sent me back here.

472
00:39:26.840 --> 00:39:28.456
What's that bringing up for you?

473
00:39:28.480 --> 00:39:31.096
We don't have to do
the therapy version of this. Cal.

474
00:39:31.120 --> 00:39:33.016
I don't think you're qualified.

475
00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:34.096
I'm sorry.

476
00:39:34.120 --> 00:39:36.096
I was just trying to help. It's fine.

477
00:39:36.120 --> 00:39:40.816
We can just be normal. you know?
We can just talk like normal.

478
00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:42.600
Well. what do you want to talk about?

479
00:39:53.760 --> 00:39:56.040
Nell. are you still there?

480
00:40:37.120 --> 00:40:42.056
Have you two had
a missing head before?

481
00:40:42.080 --> 00:40:43.616
Had a few feet.

482
00:40:43.640 --> 00:40:45.296
A couple of hands.

483
00:40:45.320 --> 00:40:47.016
Nose.

484
00:40:47.040 --> 00:40:49.256
Two big toes.

485
00:40:49.280 --> 00:40:50.480
Penis.

486
00:40:56.200 --> 00:40:58.800
Any word on the anonymous tip-off?

487
00:41:01.400 --> 00:41:03.176
Well. there's only one phone box.

488
00:41:03.200 --> 00:41:05.416
It's on Flat Hill Road by the Emporium.

489
00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:08.056
Yeah. No cameras and
covered in fingerprints.

490
00:41:08.080 --> 00:41:10.416
No. if it was the ratter.
they were definitely wearing gloves.

491
00:41:10.440 --> 00:41:15.336
We need a timeline on the people
who saw Jonas McGee alive last.

492
00:41:15.360 --> 00:41:16.496
Man Mountain.

493
00:41:16.520 --> 00:41:17.576
I have a name.

494
00:41:17.600 --> 00:41:18.840
Name?

495
00:41:20.440 --> 00:41:23.256
Stanley Honeywell.
Works at Cuttamulla Mine.

496
00:41:23.280 --> 00:41:25.040
Hello. Stanley Honeywell.

497
00:41:27.480 --> 00:41:29.336
We need to talk to him.

498
00:41:29.360 --> 00:41:32.896
The sister with the claim next door.

499
00:41:32.920 --> 00:41:34.896
Ada. yeah.

500
00:41:34.920 --> 00:41:36.776
Ada.

501
00:41:36.800 --> 00:41:40.416
OK. So. the Spaghetti Miscellaneous.
Thank you.

502
00:41:40.440 --> 00:41:42.936
The chicken. with chips a la mode.
That means "on the side".

503
00:41:42.960 --> 00:41:44.656
Thanks. And then the fish legs.

504
00:41:44.680 --> 00:41:46.040
Thanks. Thanks. Thank you.

505
00:41:50.640 --> 00:41:52.576
Are you not eating with us. Carole?

506
00:41:52.600 --> 00:41:54.800
Nah. Looks good. though.

507
00:41:56.640 --> 00:41:57.880
Carole. Ivan.

508
00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:08.256
She prefers the company of dead people.

509
00:42:08.280 --> 00:42:10.696
That checks out.

510
00:42:10.720 --> 00:42:12.456
Are you good?

511
00:42:12.480 --> 00:42:15.216
We're a long way from the ocean.

512
00:42:15.240 --> 00:42:17.360
Then why did you get the fish?

513
00:42:53.080 --> 00:42:55.880
- Are you still open?
- Closed. Sorry.

514
00:42:58.000 --> 00:42:59.576
Yeah.

515
00:42:59.600 --> 00:43:03.176
Hang on. Raf. can you get me that one?

516
00:43:03.200 --> 00:43:04.640
We've got one burger left.

517
00:43:06.360 --> 00:43:08.200
Here we go. On the house.

518
00:43:09.400 --> 00:43:10.896
Go on.

519
00:43:10.920 --> 00:43:12.536
Thank you. You're welcome.

520
00:43:12.560 --> 00:43:15.496
I went to the pub for dinner.

521
00:43:15.520 --> 00:43:17.880
I still haven't eaten.

522
00:43:42.640 --> 00:43:44.656
You...

523
00:43:44.680 --> 00:43:47.080
You left this behind at the crime scene...

524
00:43:51.280 --> 00:43:53.640
Detective Buchanan.

525
00:43:55.160 --> 00:43:56.480
It's got a ring to it.

526
00:43:58.080 --> 00:44:00.360
Hope you're proud of yourself.

527
00:44:03.400 --> 00:44:05.376
I guess.

528
00:44:05.400 --> 00:44:06.960
Well. you should be.

529
00:44:08.120 --> 00:44:09.816
If I was tough on you back then.

530
00:44:09.840 --> 00:44:13.696
I hope you can see now
it was 'cause I was...

531
00:44:13.720 --> 00:44:16.896
preparing you for the shit
that I had to deal with.

532
00:44:16.920 --> 00:44:18.376
Yeah.

533
00:44:18.400 --> 00:44:20.936
Well. water under the bridge.

534
00:44:20.960 --> 00:44:24.296
Yeah. No water up here. though.

535
00:44:24.320 --> 00:44:25.760
Or bridges.

536
00:44:28.760 --> 00:44:30.000
Need to get that?

537
00:44:31.720 --> 00:44:33.296
Nope.

538
00:44:33.320 --> 00:44:34.840
Not your boss. is it?

539
00:44:38.800 --> 00:44:40.040
How do you say his name again?

540
00:44:41.240 --> 00:44:42.976
'Lootch-itch'.

541
00:44:43.000 --> 00:44:45.216
'Lootch-itch'.

542
00:44:45.240 --> 00:44:47.280
You like him?

543
00:44:49.480 --> 00:44:50.560
Yeah.

544
00:44:52.080 --> 00:44:53.360
He seems good.

545
00:44:54.600 --> 00:44:55.600
That's good.

546
00:44:56.600 --> 00:44:58.480
It's important to have someone to trust.

547
00:45:04.480 --> 00:45:06.816
Well. I should let you go. Yeah.

548
00:45:06.840 --> 00:45:09.576
Yeah. I should get some sleep.

549
00:45:09.600 --> 00:45:10.720
Yeah.

550
00:45:12.800 --> 00:45:17.016
It took some... took some guts
coming back here. Narelle.

551
00:45:17.040 --> 00:45:18.896
I admire that.

552
00:45:18.920 --> 00:45:21.256
Not everyone who escapes the lion's den

553
00:45:21.280 --> 00:45:23.040
wants to go back for their hat.

554
00:45:24.760 --> 00:45:25.880
Night.

555
00:45:44.280 --> 00:45:46.456
Nice caravan.

556
00:45:46.480 --> 00:45:48.336
Swiss Alps.

557
00:45:48.360 --> 00:45:49.656
You've been there?

558
00:45:49.680 --> 00:45:51.296
No.

559
00:45:51.320 --> 00:45:53.256
Rafi's father bought it.

560
00:45:53.280 --> 00:45:56.016
painted it like this.
and dragged us up here.

561
00:45:56.040 --> 00:45:58.480
He lasted about as long
as the snow would have.

562
00:46:03.440 --> 00:46:04.616
That's hard... Yeah.

563
00:46:04.640 --> 00:46:05.720
For a boy.

564
00:46:07.720 --> 00:46:08.880
You got kids?

565
00:46:15.920 --> 00:46:19.056
He is a good kid. He looks like one.

566
00:46:19.080 --> 00:46:20.840
We sort of look out for each other.

567
00:46:22.640 --> 00:46:26.216
Not here for opals? God. no. No.

568
00:46:26.240 --> 00:46:28.256
Switzerland - I'm neutral.

569
00:46:28.280 --> 00:46:29.960
I'm Ivan.

570
00:46:31.480 --> 00:46:32.840
The detective.

571
00:46:34.360 --> 00:46:35.816
Billie.

572
00:46:35.840 --> 00:46:37.136
Burger maker.

573
00:46:37.160 --> 00:46:39.560
Billie. Nice to meet you.

574
00:46:40.760 --> 00:46:42.040
Welcome to hell.

575
00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:47.120
Don't let it get to you.
The heat can do really weird things.

576
00:47:44.640 --> 00:47:46.856
Where are they going?

577
00:47:46.880 --> 00:47:48.936
Iron Ring.

578
00:47:48.960 --> 00:47:50.976
What's that?

579
00:47:51.000 --> 00:47:52.320
Nothing good.

580
00:47:55.440 --> 00:47:58.280
You have one new voice message.

581
00:47:59.600 --> 00:48:00.976
Detective Buchanan.

582
00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:02.776
this is Detective Senior Sergeant
Nathan Phelan

583
00:48:02.800 --> 00:48:04.616
from Professional Standards.

584
00:48:04.640 --> 00:48:06.856
I'm calling with regard to Ivan Lucic.

585
00:48:06.880 --> 00:48:09.376
Wondering if we could find a time to talk.

586
00:48:09.400 --> 00:48:11.856
strictly off the record. of course.

587
00:48:11.880 --> 00:48:13.280
Please give me a call when you can.

588
00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:19.096
To call back. press 2-2.

589
00:48:19.120 --> 00:48:20.976
To replay the message. press 1.

590
00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:22.896
To reply. press 2.

591
00:48:22.920 --> 00:48:25.056
To send a copy. press 3.

592
00:48:25.080 --> 00:48:27.160
To delete. press 5.

593
00:49:21.120 --> 00:49:22.480
Where are we going. Mum?

594
00:49:54.960 --> 00:49:56.936
Carole called.

595
00:49:56.960 --> 00:49:59.160
Carole called you?
Yeah. We need to get to the morgue.

596
00:50:01.280 --> 00:50:03.816
You look tired.

597
00:50:03.840 --> 00:50:06.496
Is your air conditioning working?

598
00:50:06.520 --> 00:50:07.800
Yeah.

599
00:50:09.720 --> 00:50:10.920
Good.

600
00:50:18.840 --> 00:50:20.696
Hi.

601
00:50:20.720 --> 00:50:22.616
I'm Nell. This is Ivan.

602
00:50:22.640 --> 00:50:23.856
Hi.

603
00:50:23.880 --> 00:50:25.080
What's your name?

604
00:50:29.640 --> 00:50:31.296
Is someone here with you?

605
00:50:31.320 --> 00:50:32.640
Is your mum around?

606
00:50:34.120 --> 00:50:36.056
I tried to tell her the body
wasn't ready for viewing.

607
00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:38.656
He's my dad. I have a right to be here.

608
00:50:38.680 --> 00:50:39.800
What's your name?

609
00:50:41.120 --> 00:50:42.616
Elsie. Elsie.

610
00:50:42.640 --> 00:50:44.616
Do you mind if I call you Elsie?

611
00:50:44.640 --> 00:50:45.976
Yeah. it's my name...

612
00:50:46.000 --> 00:50:47.496
so that's fine.

613
00:50:47.520 --> 00:50:48.976
I'm Detective Lucic.

614
00:50:49.000 --> 00:50:51.936
We're looking into your father's death.

615
00:50:51.960 --> 00:50:53.896
Detective Buchanan.

616
00:50:53.920 --> 00:50:55.400
Sorry for your loss.

617
00:50:56.560 --> 00:50:58.080
You can't lose what you never had.

618
00:50:59.320 --> 00:51:02.256
When was the last time
you saw your father. Elsie?

619
00:51:02.280 --> 00:51:04.296
Before my daughter was born.

620
00:51:04.320 --> 00:51:05.920
You spoken to him lately?

621
00:51:07.440 --> 00:51:09.576
Well. it doesn't really matter now.

622
00:51:09.600 --> 00:51:12.440
Look. we needed his help.
so when will his affairs be settled?

623
00:51:13.720 --> 00:51:16.280
Not until we close
the investigation. Elsie.

624
00:51:23.600 --> 00:51:24.680
Right.

625
00:51:30.400 --> 00:51:32.776
Bess?

626
00:51:32.800 --> 00:51:34.560
Bess!

627
00:51:38.800 --> 00:51:40.936
Bess!

628
00:51:40.960 --> 00:51:42.600
Where is she?!

629
00:51:53.560 --> 00:51:54.800
Do it again.

630
00:51:56.880 --> 00:51:58.040
Bess?

631
00:52:07.720 --> 00:52:08.976
I was just playing.

632
00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:10.360
Hi. Elsie.

633
00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:13.000
Hello. David.

634
00:52:14.400 --> 00:52:19.520
Ivan. this is David Mamon
from The Third Row.

635
00:52:23.280 --> 00:52:27.616
Detective Ivan Lucic. Homicide.

636
00:52:27.640 --> 00:52:29.480
Must take a bit of getting used to.

637
00:52:31.200 --> 00:52:32.856
What's that?

638
00:52:32.880 --> 00:52:34.960
Having that at the back of your name.

639
00:52:39.200 --> 00:52:40.640
David Mamon.

640
00:52:43.640 --> 00:52:44.840
Homicide.

641
00:52:46.240 --> 00:52:48.976
I mean. that'll change
how you're seen. won't it?

642
00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:50.856
Well. that's who I am.

643
00:52:50.880 --> 00:52:51.896
No. that's what you do.

644
00:52:51.920 --> 00:52:54.520
Who you are is... something different.

645
00:52:55.760 --> 00:52:56.760
OK.

646
00:52:57.880 --> 00:53:00.456
You knew Jonas McGee.

647
00:53:00.480 --> 00:53:03.056
Yeah. Yeah.

648
00:53:03.080 --> 00:53:04.616
When's the last time you saw him?

649
00:53:04.640 --> 00:53:09.976
You know how. some people.
they got an aura. you know?

650
00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:12.296
You know. like. an aura. You know that?

651
00:53:12.320 --> 00:53:14.176
You know aura. yeah.

652
00:53:14.200 --> 00:53:18.720
Yeah. So. Jonas. he had an aura.

653
00:53:19.880 --> 00:53:22.976
You got an aura. It's like a child.

654
00:53:23.000 --> 00:53:25.240
Is it you or is it yours?

655
00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:32.800
You didn't answer my question.
You haven't answered mine.

656
00:53:53.640 --> 00:53:55.856
You got a place to stay?

657
00:53:55.880 --> 00:53:57.280
I can't afford a motel.

658
00:54:00.080 --> 00:54:01.680
Well. should we get you home. then?

659
00:54:09.120 --> 00:54:10.360
Nice to meet you.

660
00:54:16.480 --> 00:54:17.480
Yes?

661
00:54:19.440 --> 00:54:20.440
OK.

662
00:54:24.760 --> 00:54:26.600
That was Richter. We need to go now.

663
00:54:38.080 --> 00:54:39.160
Ivan.

664
00:56:22.400 --> 00:56:25.280
Jonas's head is pointing
his finger at you.

665
00:56:26.600 --> 00:56:27.616
How long are you gonna let

666
00:56:27.640 --> 00:56:29.256
this big-city suit swan around our town?

667
00:56:29.280 --> 00:56:33.176
I got your little note.
I don't scare that easily.

668
00:56:33.200 --> 00:56:35.536
Care to try your luck. Detective?

669
00:56:35.560 --> 00:56:37.856
This town. everything in this town.

670
00:56:37.880 --> 00:56:39.880
it's a waste of my time.

671
00:56:41.560 --> 00:56:43.816
You know. out here.
people are a lot friendlier

672
00:56:43.840 --> 00:56:46.000
once you get to know them. Detective.

673
00:56:53.280 --> 00:56:57.056
Do you feel what I'm capable of?

674
00:56:57.080 --> 00:56:58.216
Do you feel it?

675
00:56:58.240 --> 00:57:00.216
Captions by Red Bee Media.

676
00:57:00.240 --> 00:57:02.240
